# Contributing to RICK

First off — thank you. RICK started as one dad building something for his son. Every person who contributes is helping extend that to another family.

This document tells you how to get involved, regardless of your background.

-----

## We Need More Than Code

Most open source projects think contribution means pull requests. RICK needs a full community. Here’s where you can help:

|Role                 |What You’d Do                                         |
|---------------------|------------------------------------------------------|
|**Developers**       |Features, bugfixes, integrations, testing             |
|**Prompt Engineers** |Refining the autism-informed interaction style        |
|**SLPs & Clinicians**|Validating the progression model and readiness signals|
|**Designers**        |UX/UI — this has to be exceptional for our users      |
|**Families**         |Beta testing and lived experience feedback            |
|**Hardware Donors**  |GPU nodes and compute for families who can’t self-host|
|**Researchers**      |Outcome studies and clinical validation               |

No contribution is too small. Fixing a typo in the docs matters. Sharing the project with one family matters.

-----

## Code of Conduct

RICK serves a vulnerable population. We hold ourselves to a high standard.

- Be kind. Always.
- Assume good intent.
- Respect the lived experience of autistic individuals and their families — they are the experts on their own lives.
- Never share or discuss any user data, even anonymized, outside of formal research channels.
- Disagreements about code or approach are fine. Personal attacks are not.

Violations will result in removal from the project. No exceptions.

-----

## Getting Started

### 1. Fork and clone the repo

```bash
git clone https://github.com/rick-companion/rick
cd rick
```

### 2. Set up your environment

```bash
# Copy environment config
cp .env.example .env

# Start local stack
docker compose up -d
```

### 3. Install Python dependencies

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 4. Verify your setup

```bash
python -m pytest tests/
```

Full setup guide: [`/docs/self-hosting.md`](./docs/self-hosting.md)

-----

## How to Contribute

### Reporting Bugs

Open an issue and include:

- What you expected to happen
- What actually happened
- Steps to reproduce
- Your environment (OS, Docker version, GPU if relevant)

Use the `bug` label.

### Suggesting Features

Open an issue with the `enhancement` label. Describe:

- The problem you’re solving
- Who it helps
- How you’d approach it

Big ideas are welcome. We’d rather hear an ambitious idea than not.

### Submitting a Pull Request

1. Create a branch from `main`
   
   ```bash
   git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
   ```
1. Make your changes
1. Write or update tests where relevant
1. Keep commits clear and descriptive
1. Open a PR against `main` with a description of what you changed and why
1. Reference any related issues

We review all PRs as quickly as we can. We’ll always give you feedback even if we don’t merge immediately.

### Improving Prompts

The autism-informed prompt library lives in `/core/prompts/`. If you have expertise in autism, speech-language pathology, or AI prompt engineering — this is one of the highest-impact areas to contribute.

Open an issue tagged `prompts` before making large changes so we can discuss the approach first.

-----

## Clinical Contributors

If you are an SLP, psychologist, autism researcher, or other clinician:

- Review the progression model in [`/docs/progression-model.md`](./docs/progression-model.md)
- Open issues tagged `clinical` with feedback, concerns, or validation suggestions
- Reach out via GitHub Discussions if you’re interested in a formal advisory role

Your expertise shapes whether this actually works. We want you involved early.

-----

## Hardware Donations

RICK is built to run locally — but not every family has a homelab. We’re building a community compute network so families who can’t self-host can still access RICK for free.

If you want to donate hardware or contribute a compute node:

- Open an issue tagged `hardware-donation`
- Describe what you have available
- We’ll reach out to discuss how to get you set up

All hardware donors are recognized in [`CONTRIBUTORS.md`](./CONTRIBUTORS.md).

-----

## Recognition

Every contributor is recognized. Always.

- Code contributors appear in [`CONTRIBUTORS.md`](./CONTRIBUTORS.md)
- Clinical advisors are listed in [`/docs/advisors.md`](./docs/advisors.md)
- Hardware donors are listed in [`/docs/hardware-donors.md`](./docs/hardware-donors.md)
- Significant contributors may be invited to join the core maintainer team

-----

## Questions?

Open a GitHub Discussion. We’d rather answer a question than have someone stuck or unsure.

-----

*RICK started with one dad and one kid named Rick. Every contributor adds to that story.*
